douglas edwards one of the founding fathers 
of broadcast journalism signed off after more than four decades on 
the air by thanking his coworkers and his viewers during his last 
tv appearance for cbs 
and so ends the chapter of almost 46 years as this reporter 
moves on along the journey edwards 70 said on fridays midday 
cbs newsbreak 
a deep bow of gratitude love and respect to the men and women 
of cbs news and to the company for which they stand to you out 
there thank you for honoring me with your presence in my audience 
and most of all for your voices your most sweet voices douglas 
edwards cbs news new york 
edwards was the nations first nightly tv anchorman preceding 
walter cronkite in the job at cbs in 1948 
edwards joined cbs radio in 1942 and was a member of edward r 
murrows legendary london staff toward the end of world war ii he 
also served as paris bureau chief 
edwards last radio broadcast was friday night at its close 
cbs news vice president joe dembo wished edwards goodbye and 
godspeed and cbs evening news anchorman dan rather saluted him 
as one of the founding fathers of broadcast journalism 
president reagan sent a congratulatory letter calling edwards a 
consummate professional 
edwards plans to move to sarasota fla and continue lecturing 
on broadcast journalism while he starts work on a book 
